# Fluff Date: 2026-02-28 15:57:23
<overview>
<p>The Mammoth class is the largest DropShip capable of landing on a planet, serving as the backbone of bulk cargo transportation across the Inner Sphere since its introduction in 2658. Designed by Krester's Ship Construction as a massive spheroid freighter, the Mammoth dwarfs most other cargo carriers at 52,000 tons, hauling nearly 38,000 tons of goods across five enormous cargo decks. Few vessels of this scale are independently owned, with most belonging to large megacorporations or Successor State governments. Several states have modified Mammoths to serve as diatomic-hydrogen fuel tankers, while others act as fleet refueling vessels for extended operations.</p><p>The high operating and maintenance costs associated with a vessel of this immense size restrict the Mammoth's use to major trade routes between well-developed worlds, making it an uncommon but unmistakable sight wherever interstellar commerce flows at scale.</p>
</overview>

<capabilities>
<p>The 2808 production model serves as a revision of the original Mammoth adapted for the declining technological capabilities of the early Succession Wars era. The vessel retains the same overall configuration as the 2658 model, including the five cargo decks, dual cargo lifts, and four small craft bays that define the class. Cargo capacity remains at approximately 37,815 tons, and the quad-engine drive arrangement with its emergency jettison capability is preserved unchanged.</p><p>Adjustments to available manufacturing processes account for the primary differences between the two models, with component substitutions reflecting what could be reliably produced during this period. The vessel maintains the same 252 points of armor protection, 262 single heat sinks, and defensive weapons array as its predecessor. The crew complement of 63 and the same austere living arrangements remain, with the dual-occupancy berthing and limited single cabins for officers reflecting the Mammoth's design philosophy of maximizing cargo volume above all other considerations.</p>
</capabilities>

<deployment>
<p>The revised Mammoth continued in service with Successor State governments and the largest megacorporations throughout the Succession Wars and beyond. Production was maintained by Federated-Boeing Interstellar, Kathil Shipworks, New Syrtis Shipyards, and Tengo Aerospace, among others, with Deller-Bingham-Fouts also contributing to the fleet. The vessel remained the premier bulk cargo carrier across all Successor States, though the high costs of operation continued to limit its use to major trade routes between well-developed worlds. Military logistics commands valued the Mammoth for its ability to move enormous quantities of supplies in a single transit, essential for sustaining large-scale planetary campaigns.</p>
</deployment>

<history>
<p>Krester's Ship Construction introduced the Mammoth class in 2658 during the height of the Star League era, when expanding interstellar commerce demanded bulk cargo carriers of unprecedented capacity. The design proved immediately successful, with its massive cargo capacity and innovative drive system attracting contracts from the largest trading concerns and military logistics commands in the Inner Sphere. The original design was eventually sold to foreign customers, ensuring that production continued at multiple facilities even after Krester's Ship Construction itself ceased operations.</p><p>When the Star League collapsed, the Mammoth's sophisticated engineering became both a blessing and a curse. The vessel's sheer cargo capacity remained irreplaceable for bulk transport operations, but the complexity of its quad-engine drive system and advanced components made maintenance increasingly difficult as the Succession Wars eroded the Inner Sphere's technological base. Spare parts grew scarce, and operators frequently cannibalized damaged vessels to keep others flying, steadily reducing the total number in service throughout the First and Second Succession Wars.</p><p>By the late Succession Wars era, the surviving Mammoth fleet had stabilized as manufacturers adapted production methods to work within available technological capabilities. A revised model introduced around 2808 incorporated adjustments to accommodate the declining industrial base while preserving the vessel's essential cargo capacity. Production was maintained at facilities operated by Federated-Boeing Interstellar, Kathil Shipworks, Tengo Aerospace, and others across the Inner Sphere, ensuring that the Mammoth remained available to those organizations wealthy enough to operate one.</p><p>Throughout all eras, the Mammoth's role has remained consistent: moving massive quantities of goods between major trade worlds. Modified variants serving as fuel tankers have proved equally valuable, providing critical refueling capability for military fleets operating far from established supply lines. The vessel's enduring presence on every major trade route across the Inner Sphere stands as reflection of the soundness of its original design.</p>
</history>

